# $APPASERVER_HOME/INSTALL
# ------------------------
The challenge is to securely couple Appaserver, Mysql, and Apache.
For example, shell users need to access their private databases, yet
Apache needs to access all of them. Another example, Appaserver
needs to create sensitive files in $DOCUMENT_ROOT. Also, you
need to compile Appaserver which creates links to Apaches's
CGI directory.

The solution to this challenge is the Group Centric Paradigm.
See $APPASERVER_HOME/src_template/group_centric.txt . 

Appaserver's implementation of the Group Centric Paradigm 
is to create group=appaserver in /etc/group.
Then assign as group members, `who am i` and www-data.
Alternatively, you could add yourself to the existing
group=www-data. The important characteristic is the
people who compile and Apache need write access,
and everyone else can't even read.

Here are the shell installation steps:

$ cd $somewhere
$ git clone git://github.com/timhriley/appaserver.git
$ cd appaserver/src_template
$ sudo cp appaserver_template.config /etc/appaserver.config
$ sudo vi /etc/appaserver.config
vi> set mysql password
vi> set appaserver_mount_point
vi> set appaserver_group=appaserver|www-data
vi> set other configurable variables
$ sudo ./install_appaserver_profile.sh noexecute|execute
$ sudo ./install_appaserver_filesystem.sh noexecute|execute
$ sudo ./protect_appaserver_filesystem.sh noexecute|execute
$ ./install_template_database.sh noexecute|execute
$ upgrade_appaserver_database template:template

Here are the browser login steps:

1) Point your browser to: /appaserver/template
2) Login using: login_name=nobody and password=changeit

To uninstall Appaserver:
$ cd $APPASERVER_HOME/src_template
$ sudo ./uninstall_appaserver_filesystem.sh noexecute|execute

